From f65d39a41b1426efe1d6ef02f801a7e079237f3e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Anuj Gupta <anuj1072538@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 1 Jun 2026 11:00:30 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] fake_gpu_dmabuf: add controlled dma-buf exporter for deadlock
 testing
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Add a minimal kernel module and userspace test that reproduce the three
AMDGPU exporter behaviors responsible for ABBA deadlocks in the
io_uring dma-buf registered-buffer path (pavel/rw-dmabuf-v4).

The module exposes /dev/fake_gpu_dmabuf with ioctls to:

  BLOCK_MAP / UNBLOCK_MAP
    Cause map_dma_buf() to block with the resv held, simulating
    ttm_bo_validate() waiting on a GPU fence inside map_dma_buf().
    Reproduces Deadlock 1: io_uring holds resv (NULL ctx) while a second
    thread cannot wound it.

  INVAL_AND_HOLD / RELEASE_HOLD
    Lock resv, call dma_buf_invalidate_mappings(), then hold the resv
    further while waiting.  Simulates amdgpu_bo_move_notify() followed
    by KFD restore holding the resv for a VM fence wait.
    With the old async-release design, the NVMe release worker needs
    this same resv (ABBA deadlock).  With the current synchronous fix
    (io_dmabuf_drop_map runs inline under the caller's resv), this ioctl
    returns promptly — proving the fix is correct.

  HOLD_RESV / RELEASE_RESV
    Hold the resv from a kthread.  Reproduces drm_exec / KFD restore
    holding a BO resv across a fence wait window.

Only the exporter side is fake; the real io_uring → io_dmabuf_token →
nvme_pci importer path is used unchanged, so hangs produce meaningful
kernel stack traces.

Kthreads call get_dma_buf() before kthread_run() to keep the dmabuf
resv alive while the lock is held, and kref_get() to keep the buf
struct alive independently of the fd lifecycle.

The userspace selftest (tools/testing/selftests/fake_gpu/) runs four
non-NVMe sanity tests unconditionally and a fifth full end-to-end NVMe
validation test when --nvme /dev/nvmeXnY is supplied.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>
